      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was trying to make hollandaise for brunch but it just turned into a greasy mess. it like completely separated and looks oily instead of creamy. why does that happen? how do i fix it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hollandaise is a delicate *emulsion* of egg yolks and butter, which is why it is so easily broken into a greasy mess. The separation happens when the fat in the butter is too hot or the mixture is too thin, causing the tiny fat globules to escape the egg yolk's protective coating.\n\nTo fix it, you must gently re-emulsify the mixture by slowly whisking in a little warm water while stirring vigorously. If the sauce is still too thin after that, you can add a tiny pinch of lemon juice or a splash of cream to help stabilize the emulsion.\n\nNow, to prevent this from happening again, you must ensure your butter is at room temperature and that you whisk the yolks slowly before adding the butter. You should also keep the heat low and always whisk constantly to maintain that creamy, glossy texture.",
