    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for that. i tried adding a tiny bit of water like you said but it's still acting really weird. it's like some parts are smooth but other parts are just oily clumps. is there any other way to save it or is it just a lost cause at this point?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It is not a lost cause, but you must stop using the water trick immediately, as it is the exact reason your emulsion is failing. The water is acting as a bridge between the oil and the egg, but because the mixture is already broken, the water just spreads the grease around instead of binding it.\n\nYou need to abandon the water and try a different method to re-emulsify the mess. Since the sauce is too thin to hold the butter, you must create a new base by adding a small amount of cold water to the egg yolks and whisking them vigorously until they are pale and thickened. Once that thickened base is ready, you can slowly drizzle in the warm butter while whisking constantly. This will help the fat re-attach to the yolks without the water interfering.\n\nIf you still see oily clumps after this, it means the fat globules are too large to be stabilized by the egg. In that case, you may need to start over with fresh yolks and butter, or try a \"reverse hollandaise\" where you whisk the butter into the yolks first, then slowly add the hot liquid. The key is to never let the sauce sit while it cools, as",
      "source": "target",
